    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, restrict analysis to service components: [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"]. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) among these, do the following:\n1) Compute the global P95 value of that full series using all available timestamps (do not pre-filter by incident window).\n2) Filter the metric rows to the incident window: start = 2024-01-19 07:08:40 UTC, end = 2024-01-19 07:38:40 UTC (include endpoints).\n3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce a compact aggregate with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, count_points_in_window, count_points_exceeding_p95 (value >= global_p95), earliest_timestamp_exceeding_p95 (or None), max_value_in_window. \nReturn at most top 20 rows sorted by count_points_exceeding_p95 descending, then by (max_value_in_window/global_p95) descending. If a series has no rows in the incident window, omit it from the output. Keep output compact (only the specified columns)."
}

Based on metric analysis within the incident window (2024-01-19 07:08:40–07:38:40 UTC), the strongest and most persistent anomaly is a sustained socket KPI exceedance on the catalogue service starting at 2024-01-19 07:11:00 UTC. Traces were unavailable and logs showed no errors, so the metrics point to a socket-related network issue in the catalogue service as the root cause.

